		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1304270">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>kardaz</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">The Wii is like &quot;The American Idol&quot; of the consoles. The 360 amd PS3 are like the &quot;Firefly&quot;, &quot;Farscape&quot;, &quot;Dresden Files&quot;, etc. They offer more but cost more to produce and they are not mainstream.<br /></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
This simply is <i>not true</i>. <br />
<br />
I feel like I'm talking to a wall when I bring up actual sales numbers, but:<br />
<br />
There are more 360's in American homes than Wii's.<br />
Combine the 360s and PS3s in Europe and there are more in homes than Wii's.<br />
<br />
I don't feel like hunting down the Nielson's to check up on American Idol vs. one of those Sci-fi shows but I'm going to take an educated guess and say the rating difference is going to be astronomical.<br />
<br />
A more apt comparison would be comparing a reality show to a prime time network drama that is going to have to pay actors and scriptwriters. Then trying to discover the revenue vs. profit for a major Nintendo party game vs. a 360 AAA title. I don't want to write a research paper, so I am going to avoid that and I think it totally sidesteps the important point that Nintendo is the only one with truly successful shallow games (and most of their games aren't shallow to begin with).
                  
		</div>
