	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1304319">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1304319">
                  
                  I don't get it, are you guys just not noticing how normal it is for people to talk about playing video games, any video game at all? The future is not going to be about catering to people who traditionally don't play videogames, it's going to be about more people playing all kinds of videogames. Everyone getting into videogames now won't strictly continue to only buy and play casual games. There isn't something about curent gaming that only appeals to the young male demographic any more than NES games only appeal to young boys. The Wii was designed to bring in people who were intimidated by the complexity of traditional games.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Torcer Arcana</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">It's because you really can't compare a MMO to a non MMO.  Compared to other MMOs, WOW is casual, but compared to Wii Sports WoW is pretty frickn hardcore!  <br /></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
The relativity you and Ringbang mention has more to do with the barrier of entry to a genre than to the industry itself. Someone who hasn't played so much as Diner Dash isn't going to care that Warcraft 3 is less complicated than Rome:Total War if video games intimidate them. WoW's success goes well beyond &quot;well it's easier to play than EQ&quot;. Say that in a pick up group and notice how many people don't know what EQ is, or heck probably even Vanguard. They don't care that it's easier, they only care that this game is the one that had all the insane hype and buzz.<br />
<br />
<br />
I'll tell you how I think casual gaming will dominate. Someone mentioned American Idol, but that doesn't exist yet for videogames. Once it has become sufficiently mainstream, and the technological saavy of your average gamer has increased, there will be some franchise with dollar DLC that you can order from your cellphone.<br />
<br />
At the same time though, serious gaming will be bigger than ever, not weaker, thanks to a society that plays videogames the same way their parents used to watch tv.<br />
<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Agent-Jesus</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I guess the disconnect here is that I am just baffled at how people can call Halo 3 and CoD4 hardcore and call WoW casual. <br />
<br />
Yes the future (actually the present) is casual, and I never disagreed. This means games like SSB and MGS and GoW and WoW. The highest selling game on the Wii in Japan by far was SSB. It will be the same here and if Halo is hardcore, so is SSB (neither are). <br /></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
It's because this isn't about traditional hardcore vs casual issues. This is actually about traditional videogames and the new wave of videogames designed to appeal to people who were usually intimidated by the complexity of games in the past. The &quot;casual&quot; games we are talking about are the ones with extremely simplistic controls and game systems. A lot of people in this thread are calling them shallow because they can't relate to being intimidated by a video game, they already understand complex game systems. <br />
<br />
I see a lot of talk about the male demographic in this thread, but this isn't really about that. There is nothing stopping people outside that demographic from enjoying these types of games (many often do), that is a seperate issue. This is a barrier of entry issue. People who think 20 buttons are too many, or don't feel like reading a textbook to learn the game rules. A lot of people who did not grow up with a gamepad in their hands feel ridiculous trying to figure it out, and would rather just not bother. The Wii remedies that with simple controls and enough buzz that no one has to be embarrassed about trying it out. The question is going to be retention and resulting movement in the industry as the new gamers shuffle and find how far into normal gaming they want to go.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
